UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1909
1 A RESOLUTION honoring the life and accomplishments of former Kentucky
2 Governor Martha Layne Collins.
3 WHEREAS, Martha Layne Hall was born on December 7, 1936, in Shelby County,
4 Kentucky, to the late Everett L. and Mary Lorena Taylor Hall. She grew up in Bagdad,
5 Kentucky, and graduated from Shelbyville High School; and
6 WHEREAS, in 1959, Martha Layne Hall earned her Bachelor of Science from the
7 University of Kentucky, and won the title of the Kentucky Derby Queen; and
8 WHEREAS, while student teaching in Scott County, Martha Layne Hall met and
9 married a Georgetown College graduate, Bill Collins. While her husband pursued
10 dentistry at the University of Louisville, they began their life together in Louisville,
11 Kentucky, and she began teaching in the Jefferson County Public Schools; and
12 WHEREAS, after moving to Woodford County and continuing to teach in the
13 public schools, Martha Layne Collins organized Woodford County's first Junior Miss
14 Pageant, and became known for her organizational skills; and
15 WHEREAS, in 1971, Martha Layne Collins became an active participant in
16 politics, and she applied her keen organizational skills and her ability to collaborate,
17 corral, and build connections with people from all backgrounds to become an
18 instrumental aide for Wendell Ford during his campaign for Governor; and
19 WHEREAS, her efforts in the successful campaign were recognized by the newly
20 elected Governor Ford, as she was named Kentucky's Democratic national
21 committeewoman; and
22 WHEREAS, in 1975, Martha Layne Collins won the election to serve as Clerk of
23 the Kentucky Court of Appeals. When that elected office was eliminated by
24 constitutional reform in 1976, she became the first Clerk of the new Supreme Court of
25 Kentucky and the first Clerk of the new Kentucky Court of Appeals. Always an educator
26 at heart, she created an educational program for county officials, school systems, and the
27 citizens of the Commonwealth to understand the constitutional changes; and
