UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1909
1 WHEREAS, in 1979, Martha Layne Collins earned the nomination for Lieutenant
2 Governor as the only woman in a large field of candidates. She was part of the winning
3 ticket, and served alongside Governor John Y. Brown, Jr. as the Commonwealth's
4 Lieutenant Governor through 1983; and
5 WHEREAS, during her role as Lieutenant Governor, Martha Layne Collins stepped
6 into the Governor's ceremonial responsibilities that provided the opportunity for her to
7 spend time across the state getting to know individuals in communities, while also being
8 seen and being accessible to the public; and
9 WHEREAS, in 1983, Martha Layne Collins chose to campaign for Governor,
10 where she promoted her ideals that government should be about "service, promptness,
11 and accessibility," and it was the handshakes and connections made across the
12 Commonwealth that contributed to the deciding difference as she won a close race for
13 Governor; and
14 WHEREAS, as the first woman to hold the office of Governor in the
15 Commonwealth of Kentucky, Martha Layne Collins continued to break ceilings by
16 championing education reforms and economic and workforce development initiatives to
17 set the precedent and foundation for record growth and investment in the state; and
18 WHEREAS, Governor Martha Layne Collins was the driving force to successfully
19 recruit and forge the historic partnership with Toyota Motor Manufacturing to establish
20 and invest in a manufacturing plant in Georgetown, Kentucky. After breaking ground in
21 1986, the first Toyota Camry rolled off the line in May 1988, and the operations have
22 continued to expand. Toyota Motor Manufacturing Kentucky is now Toyota's largest
23 vehicle plant in the world, employs over 9,000 individuals, and has invested over $154
24 million in community and educational initiatives; and
25 WHEREAS, during the defense of budgetary measures in Governor Martha Layne
26 Collins's administration of the budget, a pivotal Kentucky Supreme Court case decision
27 in Com. ex rel. Armstrong v. Collins cemented the ability of the General Assembly to
Page 2 of 4
XXXX 1/22/2026 1:23 PM Jacketed

UNOFFICIAL COPY 26 RS BR 1909
1 temporarily amend or suspend an existing statute in a budget bill, and established that the
2 power of the dollar is held by the authority of the legislative branch; and
3 WHEREAS, during her tenure as Governor, Martha Layne Collins created the
4 Governor's School for the Arts (GSA). In 1987, the inaugural class hosted 120 of
5 Kentucky's most promising high school sophomore and junior artists with talents in six
6 disciplines for three weeks of focused, collaborative, and innovative quality instruction
7 that was not previously accessible. Decades later, the legacy established by Governor
8 Martha Layne Collins in GSA has impacted well over 5,000 students, and each summer
9 the program now reaches over 500 artists in 10 different art disciplines; and
10 WHEREAS, the successes and lasting impact of Martha Layne Collins as Governor
11 of Kentucky are numerous and varied, as demonstrated by projects and efforts in
12 education reform, economic development, energy, and the environment; and
13 WHEREAS, even as her service to the Commonwealth as Governor concluded in
14 1987, Martha Layne Collins continued her interests in education and proven business
15 acumen, serving as president of St. Catharine College for six years, the Executive-in-
16 Residence at the University of Louisville's School of Business, director of the
17 International Business and Management Center at the University of Kentucky's Carol
18 Martin Gatton College of Business and Economics, and a Resident Fellow at the Harvard
19 Kennedy School Institute of Politics; and
20 WHEREAS, from 1998 to 2012, Martha Layne Collins served as an Executive
21 Scholar in Residence at Georgetown College, and is remembered by her powerful
22 presence on campus, her strength in leadership, and her distinguishing ability to form
23 connections among people; and
24 WHEREAS, Martha Layne Collins passed away peacefully on November 1, 2025,
25 at the age of 88. She is survived by her husband, Dr. Bill Collins; her son, Steve (Diane)
26 Collins; her daughter, Marla Collins (Dudley) Webb; and her grandchildren, Dr. Taylor
27 Collins, Catherine Collins (Preston) Messer, Alex Webb, Will (Mary) Webb, and Ellie
Page 3 of 4
